Touched objects analysis

Luise Rauer

23 7 2022

Summary & questions

  • Some unusual results from DADA2 (see processing markdown)
  • Strong batch effect
  • Gate lion and Tendaguru appear as objects in both batches, might be an opportunity to compare samples between batches?
  • Major problem: distinction between skin bacteria, contaminants/controls, and the surface microbiome of inanimate objects - what kind of microbiome are we expecting in untouched objects?
  • What are BS negative controls?

Analysis

The second batch has slightly lower reads before denoising, but additionally loses a great proportion of reads during quality filtering (= has lower quality scores, as noted earlier). After denoising, second batch has roughly two orders of magnitude lower reads then the first batch, and by itself really low reads.
The track table confirms that the first batch keeps 80% of sequences during denoising, and the second batch keeps only 9% of sequences on average. DADA2 filtering parameter maxEE could be increased a little to recover more reads, particularly in the second batch.

Sample composition

# Function to generate plots of taxonomic sample composition
Taxonomy_plot <- function(seqtab_f, level, top_number, metafile, metavar){
  # Subset sample ids
  sample_ids <- sample.names[sample.names %in% colnames(seqtab_f)]
  # Scale to 100%
  seqtab_f[sample_ids] <- apply(seqtab_f[sample_ids], 2, function(x) {x/sum(x)})
  # Keep only selected taxonomic level
  seqtab_f <- seqtab_f[, c(sample_ids, level)]
  # Replace missing annotation
  seqtab_f[, level][is.na(seqtab_f[, level]) | seqtab_f[, level] == ""] <- 
    "Unknown"
  # Sum up frequencies with identical taxonomy
  seqtab_f <- seqtab_f %>% 
    group_by(.data[[level]]) %>%
    summarise(across(.cols = where(is.numeric), .fns = sum, .names = "{col}")) %>%
    as.data.frame()
  # Put taxonomic level as rownames
  rownames(seqtab_f) <- seqtab_f[, level]
  seqtab_f[, level] <- NULL
  seqtab_f <- as.data.frame(t(seqtab_f))
  # Merge with metainformation
  seqtab_f <- merge(seqtab_f, metafile[, colnames(metafile) == metavar, drop = F], 
                    by = 0, all = F)
  seqtab_f[[metavar]] <- as.character(seqtab_f[[metavar]])
  # Build mean frequency per selected group
  seqtab_f <- seqtab_f %>%
    group_by(.data[[metavar]]) %>%
    summarise(across(.cols = where(is.numeric), .fns = function(x) 
      {mean(x, na.rm = T)}, .names = "{col}")) %>%
    as.data.frame()
  seqtab_f[[metavar]][is.na(seqtab_f[[metavar]])] <- "missing"
  # Select top taxa per group or overall
  top_taxa <- seqtab_f %>%
    select_if(is.numeric) %>%
    colMeans(., na.rm = T) %>% 
    sort(decreasing = TRUE)
  top_taxa <- names(top_taxa[1:top_number])
  # Summarise other taxa into "Others"
  top_taxa <- sort(top_taxa)
  taxonomy_others <- seqtab_f %>% 
    select_if(is.numeric) %>%
    select(-all_of(top_taxa)) %>%
    rowSums() %>% 
    data.frame
  colnames(taxonomy_others) <- "Others"
  # Merge taxonomy with others
  seqtab_f <- merge(
    taxonomy_others,
    seqtab_f[, c(top_taxa, metavar)], by = 0, all = TRUE)
  seqtab_f["Row.names"] <- NULL
  # Plot the result
  seqtab_f <- pivot_longer(
    seqtab_f, 1:(top_number+1),
    names_to = "Taxonomy",
    values_to = "Abundance")
  taxonomy_plot <- ggplot() +
    geom_bar(data = seqtab_f, 
             aes(x = !!sym(metavar), y = !!sym("Abundance"), fill = Taxonomy),
             position = "fill", stat = "identity") + 
    scale_fill_manual(values = setNames(c("grey40", "grey80", theme_colours[1:length(top_taxa)]),
                                        c("Unknown", "Others", top_taxa))) +
    ylab("Relative abundance") +
    theme_classic() +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 1)) +
    scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0, 0)) 
  return(list(seqtab_f, taxonomy_plot))
}

# Run taxonomy function for all samples
Tax_all <- Taxonomy_plot(seqtab.final, "Mixed_genus", 20, metadata,
                         "sample_id")
Tax_all[[2]] +
  scale_x_discrete(limits = metadata$sample_id) +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_blank())
## Warning: Removed 42 rows containing missing values (position_stack).

Apart from differences in sequencing depths, there are visible differences in sample composition between the two batches, particularly in the proportion of unknown genera - thus, analyses should be separated by batches.
This batch effect confirms that we cannot simply combine this data with publically available skin microbiome data.

Ideas to overcome batch effect:

  • Downsampling / rarefaction of microbiome data to align sequencing depths per batch?
  • Proof that data can be combined by using several replicates of two types of positive controls per batch, to show that samples cluster by original sample composition, and not by batch (but this requires new data collection/resequencing).

  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust = 1))

Even without differential abundance analysis, we can see common skin inhabitants in the touched samples (e.g.Staphylococcus, Corynebacterium), but also in all samples (e.g.Acinetobacter, Sphingomonas), or even only in untouched samples (e.g.Moraxella, Micrococcus).
Negative controls contain genera that have been found previously in negative controls, and that are rather not skin-associated (e.g.Burkholderia, Stenotrophomonas, Pseudomonas (the latter is also skin-associated)).
